column1: Which presidential candidate will win Ohio?
column5: ['The Democratic Party candidate', 'The Republican Party candidate', 'Someone else']
column6: ['Elections and Referenda']
Expected

While Ohio has had a long standing reputation as a swing state, it has trended more reliably red for the past several elections. Based on the demographics in Ohio outside of the major city centers (largely white and rural), I think that gives Trump the edge in the Buckeye state

While it seems that Biden has a lead in the United States as a whole right now, Ohio tends to lean Republican more than Democrat. An important consideration is that while the polling strategies and methodologies have improved since 2016, it seems that key battleground states were predicted impressively wrong. So while the polls are showing a close race, I think that we have to factor in that there is a strong Republican lean in Ohio that has been overlooked before. That is why I am giving an edge to Trump over Biden

On eve of election, looks like it will be close, with slight Trump win in the end. Dem early in person voting, traditionally one of the strongest parts of their GOTV operation is a dumpster fire. Mail in voting mostly cannibalizing their high propensity E-day base. Ohio has bucked the national trend of increasing blue margins and gone the opposite way, having lopsided Republican victories in 2014, 2016, and electing all save one Republican statewide offices in the blue wave of 2018. The margin of victories in 2014 and 2016 for Republican candidates were shockingly large in comparison to many other purple states in 2014/2016. Stagnant demography, mediocre but not terrible job prospects, and exporting of college educated youth to trendy coastal or sunbelt cities makes the education gap less important. Lastly, the Democrats have spent far too little time and money speaking to non college educated white women while fighting tooth and nail for every upscale chardonnay mom.

This forecast was programmatically produced by taking the (deluxe) 538 prediction and making a calibration adjustment unless this brought probability to <10%. Recommended reading: Information, incentives, and goals in election forecasts, by Gelman et al. (http://www.stat.columbia.edu/~gelman/research/unpublished/forecast_incentives3.pdf)
